1
00:00:02,006 --> 00:00:03,883
<i>Previously on</i> Dexter...

2
00:00:05,301 --> 00:00:06,969
You need to kill it.

3
00:00:07,094 --> 00:00:08,387
No, I-I can't.

4
00:00:08,513 --> 00:00:11,098
What's the real reason
you're stalling on killing Trinity?

5
00:00:11,224 --> 00:00:13,518
I still have things
to learn from him.

6
00:00:13,643 --> 00:00:16,062
Judging from the spray,
we're looking at somebody tall,

7
00:00:16,187 --> 00:00:17,647
over six feet.

8
00:00:17,772 --> 00:00:19,565
<i>He moved the arm...</i>

9
00:00:19,732 --> 00:00:21,192
<i>for a reason.</i>

10
00:00:21,317 --> 00:00:23,694
That smudge you found
at the crime scene?

11
00:00:23,819 --> 00:00:26,155
Cremated human remains.

12
00:00:26,280 --> 00:00:27,782
We got the killer's goddamn DNA?

13
00:00:27,907 --> 00:00:30,368
The killer is related
to the human remains.

14
00:00:30,493 --> 00:00:32,161
Same family. The same DNA.

15
00:00:32,328 --> 00:00:34,997
He keeps his family
with him all the time.

16
00:00:35,164 --> 00:00:36,249
Vera Mitchell.

17
00:00:36,415 --> 00:00:38,793
<i>Sister of Arthur Mitchell.</i>

18
00:00:38,918 --> 00:00:40,127
<i>Found dead in a...</i>

19
00:00:40,253 --> 00:00:41,212
Bathtub.

20
00:00:41,337 --> 00:00:43,881
<i>This is Arthur Mitchell at his core.</i>

21
00:00:44,006 --> 00:00:46,926
<i>Is there something in his DNA
that lets him keep a family,</i>

22
00:00:47,051 --> 00:00:49,262
<i>some magic gene I'm missing?</i>

23
00:00:49,387 --> 00:00:51,180
I just got the official
go-ahead from LaGuerta

24
00:00:51,305 --> 00:00:53,224
to open a Trinity Killer investigation.

25
00:00:53,349 --> 00:00:54,517
What's that mean?

26
00:00:54,642 --> 00:00:57,353
I realised if I pitched
the entire Trinity theory

27
00:00:57,478 --> 00:00:59,564
and I added that he also
shot me and Lundy,

28
00:00:59,689 --> 00:01:00,773
look like a fucking lunatic,

29
00:01:00,898 --> 00:01:03,067
so I boiled it down
to the bludgeonings.

30
00:01:03,192 --> 00:01:05,653
I am no longer seeing
Lieutenant LaGuerta.

31
00:01:05,778 --> 00:01:07,405
We broke up, officially.

32
00:01:07,530 --> 00:01:10,366
If I find out this is bullshit,
there will be consequences -

33
00:01:10,491 --> 00:01:13,411
severe, career-ending
consequences.

34
00:01:13,536 --> 00:01:14,745
Who are you?

35
00:01:14,870 --> 00:01:16,789
I'm the person
who's going to keep you

36
00:01:16,914 --> 00:01:18,457
from killing any more women.

37
00:01:18,624 --> 00:01:20,042
I didn't fucking kill them!

38
00:01:20,209 --> 00:01:22,795
Because of my pictures,
those women will live on for ever!

39
00:01:22,920 --> 00:01:25,214
Nothing lasts for ever.

40
00:01:26,173 --> 00:01:28,384
- Isn't that...
- Farrow's assistant.

41
00:01:28,551 --> 00:01:30,761
I just arrested him for
the murder of Estrella Carazo.

42
00:01:30,886 --> 00:01:32,346
But, no, I thought...

43
00:01:32,513 --> 00:01:34,557
Yeah, at first it looked like Farrow,
but this is airtight.

44
00:01:34,682 --> 00:01:37,226
We got DNA evidence.
We got everything.

45
00:01:37,351 --> 00:01:39,645
I killed an innocent man.

46
00:03:39,390 --> 00:03:42,226
<i>So I made a mistake.
It could've happened to anyone -</i>

47
00:03:42,351 --> 00:03:44,603
<i>well, any murderer-</i>

48
00:03:44,729 --> 00:03:46,313
<i>not that murderers typically care</i>

49
00:03:46,439 --> 00:03:49,024
<i>whether their victims
are innocent or not.</i>

50
00:03:49,191 --> 00:03:51,444
<i>But why is it eating at me?</i>

51
00:03:55,781 --> 00:03:59,034
<i>Jonathan Farrow - S&M photographer,</i>

52
00:03:59,201 --> 00:04:01,120
<i>abuser of women,</i>

53
00:04:01,245 --> 00:04:03,247
<i>asshole, but not a killer-</i>

54
00:04:03,372 --> 00:04:05,708
<i>not up to Harry's code.</i>

55
00:04:05,875 --> 00:04:07,168
<i>Yet I killed him.</i>

56
00:04:07,293 --> 00:04:09,086
<i>Now I'm...</i>

57
00:04:10,045 --> 00:04:12,214
<i>uncomfortable.</i>

58
00:04:14,216 --> 00:04:16,844
<i>It should've been
Arthur Mitchell on my table.</i>

59
00:04:18,512 --> 00:04:20,681
<i>Trinity, shooter of my sister.</i>

60
00:04:20,806 --> 00:04:22,475
<i>I should've...</i>

61
00:04:23,434 --> 00:04:27,021
<i>No, no "should'ves".
I don't do "should'ves". That's not me.</i>

62
00:04:30,274 --> 00:04:31,525
This isn't me.

63
00:04:31,692 --> 00:04:33,402
Aah, shit.

64
00:04:33,527 --> 00:04:36,113
<i>I just need to stop thinking about it.</i>

65
00:04:36,238 --> 00:04:37,823
Jonathan Farrow...

66
00:04:37,948 --> 00:04:41,118
originally a suspect,
now possibly a victim.

67
00:04:41,243 --> 00:04:43,245
<i>It was a mistake, for fuck's sake.</i>

68
00:04:43,412 --> 00:04:45,748
Farrow disappeared
right before his assistant,

69
00:04:45,873 --> 00:04:48,959
Timothy Brand, confessed
to murdering those models.

70
00:04:49,084 --> 00:04:51,378
Missing persons
has been investigating,

71
00:04:51,504 --> 00:04:52,963
and now they're passing it on to us.

72
00:04:53,088 --> 00:04:54,590
You think Brand killed Farrow?

73
00:04:54,715 --> 00:04:57,426
Maybe he found out what Brand
was up to, it's hard to say.

74
00:04:57,551 --> 00:05:00,095
Soderquist, Yale, stay with Farrow.

75
00:05:00,221 --> 00:05:02,181
Brand probably
turned him into gator bait.

76
00:05:02,306 --> 00:05:03,724
<i>I wish I could take comfort</i>

77
00:05:03,849 --> 00:05:05,935
<i>that my crime
has been pinned on Brand.</i>

78
00:05:06,101 --> 00:05:07,895
<i>But I can't.</i>

79
00:05:08,020 --> 00:05:10,147
What is wrong with you?

80
00:05:10,272 --> 00:05:11,524
I don't know.

81
00:05:11,649 --> 00:05:15,152
OK, moving on. Morgan...
what do we have on your bludgeonings?

82
00:05:15,277 --> 00:05:17,446
Maybe this'll cheer you up.

83
00:05:17,571 --> 00:05:20,533
<i>Not if you're making headway on Trinity.</i>

84
00:05:24,954 --> 00:05:27,248
We've got a serial bludgeoner.

85
00:05:27,373 --> 00:05:29,750
The victims are all men in their 40s.

86
00:05:29,917 --> 00:05:31,502
I've got cases
dating back 30 years,

87
00:05:31,669 --> 00:05:35,339
which most likely puts
our bludgeoner in his 50s or 60s.

88
00:05:35,506 --> 00:05:37,758
The break in the case
came with the discovery

89
00:05:37,925 --> 00:05:39,802
of the human ash
he left behind,

90
00:05:39,969 --> 00:05:41,929
along with his own saliva -

91
00:05:42,054 --> 00:05:43,264
read DNA.

92
00:05:43,389 --> 00:05:45,599
You're welcome.
Just doing my job.

93
00:05:45,724 --> 00:05:48,853
The killer leaves the ash
as his sick-ass signature,

94
00:05:49,061 --> 00:05:51,814
making his vics point at it postmortem.

95
00:05:51,981 --> 00:05:54,149
I can't be sure
all of these are ash marks,

96
00:05:54,316 --> 00:05:57,027
but the finger-pointing indicates
a strong possibility that...

97
00:05:57,778 --> 00:05:59,530
How'd that get in there?

98
00:06:01,198 --> 00:06:03,659
No, whoa. Could you go back?

99
00:06:04,743 --> 00:06:06,537
Go back.

100
00:06:08,330 --> 00:06:09,915
This isn't a bludgeoning.

101
00:06:10,082 --> 00:06:11,625
No.

102
00:06:12,835 --> 00:06:16,255
Yet the victim's finger seems
to be pointing towards a smudge.

103
00:06:16,380 --> 00:06:17,840
Ash?

104
00:06:18,549 --> 00:06:19,758
<i>Don't do it, Deb.</i>

105
00:06:22,845 --> 00:06:24,263
Yeah, probably.

106
00:06:24,388 --> 00:06:29,935
When you presented this case to me,
you said it was limited to a bludgeoner.

107
00:06:32,229 --> 00:06:35,608
So how about we hear all of it,
Detective Morgan?

108
00:06:35,733 --> 00:06:37,568
<i>It's gonna sound insane...</i>

109
00:06:37,693 --> 00:06:39,403
<i>I hope.</i>

110
00:06:40,571 --> 00:06:43,949
All right.
I found possible smudges

111
00:06:44,116 --> 00:06:47,202
in several old bathtub killings.

112
00:06:48,329 --> 00:06:50,873
Also several jumper suicides.

113
00:06:50,998 --> 00:06:52,708
And that's the pattern -

114
00:06:52,833 --> 00:06:55,127
bathtub, jumper, bludgeon -

115
00:06:55,252 --> 00:06:57,379
all in close succession.

116
00:06:57,504 --> 00:07:00,883
One cycle of three vics
every year or so,

117
00:07:01,050 --> 00:07:02,760
possibly for 30 years.

118
00:07:02,885 --> 00:07:04,803
Different cities, different states.

119
00:07:04,929 --> 00:07:08,057
It's a...a trinity of victims...

120
00:07:08,974 --> 00:07:11,602
which is why Frank Lundy
called him the Trinity Killer.

121
00:07:11,727 --> 00:07:14,229
- This is an FBI case?
- The FBI never bought it.

122
00:07:14,355 --> 00:07:15,689
Yet we're supposed to.

123
00:07:15,814 --> 00:07:18,776
Lundy came to Miami
to hunt this guy.

124
00:07:20,402 --> 00:07:24,281
I think he got too close,
and I think it got him killed and me shot.

125
00:07:25,240 --> 00:07:30,371
So this Trinity Killer
did that to you?

126
00:07:30,496 --> 00:07:33,707
<i>Come on, LaGuerta,
say it's far-fetched.</i>

127
00:07:36,794 --> 00:07:38,128
Go on.

128
00:07:38,295 --> 00:07:41,090
<i>Great, like I need you people
getting in my way.</i>

129
00:07:41,256 --> 00:07:44,259
<i>Well, Trinity is past his due date.
This just confirms it.</i>

130
00:07:44,426 --> 00:07:46,929
Dex. Can you believe it?

131
00:07:47,054 --> 00:07:50,224
- Yeah, you really did it.
- I kept Lundy's legacy alive.

132
00:07:50,349 --> 00:07:51,725
I even got the bosses on board.

133
00:07:51,850 --> 00:07:54,645
Detective Morgan, my office.

134
00:07:54,770 --> 00:07:56,522
Is that a commendation I smell?

135
00:07:56,647 --> 00:07:57,898
Go get 'em, tiger.

136
00:07:58,023 --> 00:07:59,525
Ess.

137
00:07:59,650 --> 00:08:01,110
Tigress.

138
00:08:05,280 --> 00:08:07,866
Dex. Hey, buddy.

139
00:08:07,992 --> 00:08:10,077
<i>Keep walking. Not in the mood.</i>

140
00:08:10,202 --> 00:08:11,704
Halftime?

141
00:08:11,829 --> 00:08:14,331
It's called lunch, buddy.

142
00:08:14,456 --> 00:08:16,166
Off campus, as usual.

143
00:08:18,377 --> 00:08:21,088
<i>I really do need to stab something.</i>

144
00:09:12,014 --> 00:09:14,058
<i>The Trinity Killer.</i>

145
00:09:16,560 --> 00:09:18,062
<i>This is good.</i>

146
00:09:18,187 --> 00:09:20,773
<i>There's no question of his guilt,</i>

147
00:09:20,898 --> 00:09:23,192
<i>and I could use some certainty.</i>

148
00:09:23,317 --> 00:09:25,736
Hey, Jonah,
how those wheels holding up?

149
00:09:25,861 --> 00:09:27,488
Like a dream, Mr Butler.

150
00:09:27,613 --> 00:09:29,239
Like a real nice dream.

151
00:09:29,364 --> 00:09:31,158
Kyle!

152
00:09:32,701 --> 00:09:36,038
Hey. What brings you here
this fine day?

153
00:09:36,163 --> 00:09:37,915
Ah, just checking in.

154
00:09:38,040 --> 00:09:40,084
You know, after the...

155
00:09:40,209 --> 00:09:42,461
...deer.
Wanted to make sure you're OK.

156
00:09:42,628 --> 00:09:45,756
Oh, that's kind of you,
but I've put it out of my mind,

157
00:09:45,881 --> 00:09:48,175
no need to dwell.

158
00:09:48,300 --> 00:09:49,843
You can just do that?

159
00:09:49,968 --> 00:09:53,597
No, no, no.
Smooth, circular motion, son,

160
00:09:53,722 --> 00:09:56,183
- and the paint job will last for years.
- I got it, Dad.

161
00:09:56,308 --> 00:09:58,227
If you've got it,
I wouldn't have to remind you.

162
00:09:58,352 --> 00:10:01,021
There are two ways to do things.
Why not choose the right way?

163
00:10:01,146 --> 00:10:03,190
<i>Small cracks in the perfect family,</i>

164
00:10:03,315 --> 00:10:06,235
<i>which makes them perfectly normal.</i>

165
00:10:09,780 --> 00:10:11,615
- Kyle, hello.
- Hey.

166
00:10:11,740 --> 00:10:15,410
Honey, your clothes are clean,
folded, and ready to be packed.

167
00:10:16,245 --> 00:10:17,579
Going out of town?

168
00:10:17,704 --> 00:10:19,414
- Yeah, Tampa.
- Oh.

169
00:10:19,540 --> 00:10:20,666
A Four Walls build.

170
00:10:20,791 --> 00:10:23,877
<i>An out-of-town build - is his cycle
starting over again already?</i>

171
00:10:24,002 --> 00:10:25,337
Rebecca.

172
00:10:25,462 --> 00:10:28,132
The ground needs
to be really soaked.

173
00:10:28,257 --> 00:10:30,676
A good soaking, or all these
flowers are just gonna die.

174
00:10:30,801 --> 00:10:32,261
OK, sorry.

175
00:10:34,346 --> 00:10:36,181
So, Tampa -
the whole family going?

176
00:10:36,306 --> 00:10:38,016
No, not on out-of-towners.

177
00:10:38,142 --> 00:10:39,893
It's too expensive to put 'em all up.

178
00:10:40,018 --> 00:10:41,478
Oh, admit it, Arthur.

179
00:10:41,603 --> 00:10:44,148
You enjoy those vacations from us.

180
00:10:44,273 --> 00:10:47,276
He always comes home
so relaxed.

181
00:10:47,401 --> 00:10:49,528
I'm sure.

182
00:10:49,695 --> 00:10:53,157
- You leaving today?
- No, tomorrow, right from work.

183
00:10:53,323 --> 00:10:54,867
<i>There's the where and the when.</i>

184
00:10:54,992 --> 00:10:58,245
<i>An out-of-town kill -
Trinity's own MO.</i>

185
00:10:58,370 --> 00:10:59,913
<i>How poetic.</i>

186
00:11:00,038 --> 00:11:01,331
Well, happy travels.

187
00:11:01,456 --> 00:11:03,750
Take care, Kyle.

188
00:11:03,876 --> 00:11:05,878
<i>Now I need to come up
with my own where and when</i>

189
00:11:06,044 --> 00:11:09,464
<i>to convince my boss
and my wife to let me leave.</i>

190
00:11:12,593 --> 00:11:16,013
<i>All I need is some convention
that smells a little like blood spatter,</i>

191
00:11:16,138 --> 00:11:18,849
<i>something science-y.</i>

192
00:11:19,600 --> 00:11:21,518
<i>Brake and muffler exhibit - no.</i>

193
00:11:21,685 --> 00:11:24,229
<i>Knitting and needlepoint
convention -</i>

194
00:11:24,354 --> 00:11:26,523
<i>no blood there unless
someone impales themselves.</i>

195
00:11:26,690 --> 00:11:28,984
<i>A trade show convention.</i>

196
00:11:30,485 --> 00:11:33,030
Wow, a convention on conventions.

197
00:11:37,826 --> 00:11:39,453
Remember me?

198
00:11:40,579 --> 00:11:42,915
Debra Morgan, sister.

199
00:11:43,040 --> 00:11:45,292
Debra Morgan,
former detective on the Trinity case.

200
00:11:45,459 --> 00:11:46,543
Former?

201
00:11:46,710 --> 00:11:48,420
Fucking LaGuerta
took me off the case,

202
00:11:48,629 --> 00:11:51,506
'cause officially I'm a victim
of this cocksucker's crimes.

203
00:11:53,425 --> 00:11:55,052
That's too bad.

204
00:11:55,177 --> 00:11:56,762
Too bad?

205
00:11:57,971 --> 00:11:59,681
It fucking sucks.

206
00:12:01,225 --> 00:12:03,227
Well, the bright side
is this frees you up

207
00:12:03,393 --> 00:12:06,396
to help the department
in so many ways.

208
00:12:06,521 --> 00:12:08,941
In the course of one day,

209
00:12:09,066 --> 00:12:13,362
I go from bringing in the biggest case
Miami Metro has ever seen

210
00:12:13,487 --> 00:12:15,530
to being "freed up in so many ways"?

211
00:12:17,991 --> 00:12:20,661
I love you, bro, but sometimes
you're a fucking 'tard.

212
00:12:20,786 --> 00:12:22,663
Yeah, I know.

213
00:12:28,877 --> 00:12:30,712
Tampa. What the hell's in Tampa?

214
00:12:34,299 --> 00:12:35,968
Something science-y.

215
00:12:36,093 --> 00:12:38,303
A crime scene is basically
a micro-climate

216
00:12:38,428 --> 00:12:39,638
subject to so many variables.

217
00:12:39,763 --> 00:12:42,349
In the world of blood spatter,
those variables can mean the difference

218
00:12:42,474 --> 00:12:44,268
between good science
and the guilty going free.

219
00:12:44,393 --> 00:12:46,645
Everything from the anomalous
effects of barometric pressure

220
00:12:46,770 --> 00:12:49,773
on particulate liquids
in a high-humidity environment

221
00:12:49,898 --> 00:12:51,942
- to the ionisation of...
- Point, please.

222
00:12:52,067 --> 00:12:53,318
Oh.

223
00:12:53,443 --> 00:12:55,529
Meteorological conference, Tampa.

224
00:12:56,488 --> 00:12:58,615
If I let you go, will you stop talking?

225
00:12:58,740 --> 00:13:01,410
You see, learning even more
about haemoglobin dispersion

226
00:13:01,576 --> 00:13:04,579
and the magnetic effects of lightning
in the case of severe thunderstorms

227
00:13:04,746 --> 00:13:05,872
could prove invaluable,

228
00:13:05,998 --> 00:13:08,375
because it can all be
considered causal

229
00:13:08,500 --> 00:13:10,794
in the determination
of bloodstain analysis.

230
00:13:17,426 --> 00:13:18,468
Is that it?

231
00:13:18,593 --> 00:13:20,804
That's all I could come up with.

232
00:13:20,929 --> 00:13:23,724
Well, it sounds like you're very excited
about this conference.

233
00:13:23,849 --> 00:13:27,352
Not to mention how it will look
when my salary review comes up.

234
00:13:27,477 --> 00:13:29,938
We could start paying
for your college.

235
00:13:30,105 --> 00:13:32,482
I love your dedication...

236
00:13:32,607 --> 00:13:35,193
to work, to this family.

237
00:13:35,319 --> 00:13:37,404
It's one of the reasons
why I married you.

238
00:13:37,529 --> 00:13:39,823
- One of the many, right?
- Right.

239
00:13:39,990 --> 00:13:41,783
You know, and, actually,

240
00:13:41,908 --> 00:13:43,618
Elliot's taking the kids fishing,

241
00:13:43,744 --> 00:13:46,747
so they'll be busy
at least one of those days.

242
00:13:46,872 --> 00:13:49,708
He's a good neighbour, that Elliot.

243
00:13:49,833 --> 00:13:52,502
But I do need some space too,

244
00:13:52,711 --> 00:13:54,212
so I'll trade you.

245
00:13:54,338 --> 00:13:56,256
I'll cover the kids this weekend,

246
00:13:56,381 --> 00:13:58,467
and you cover them Tuesday nights
when I go to yoga?

247
00:13:58,592 --> 00:14:00,010
Yoga?

248
00:14:00,177 --> 00:14:01,553
It's the new me.

249
00:14:01,678 --> 00:14:03,347
Well, I like the new you.

250
00:14:06,058 --> 00:14:07,809
<i>Though scheduling my activities</i>

251
00:14:07,934 --> 00:14:11,521
<i>around her downward-facing dog
could prove challenging.</i>

252
00:14:13,732 --> 00:14:15,692
<i>I'll dwell on that later.</i>

253
00:14:25,118 --> 00:14:28,497
<i>What does one pack
for an out-of-town kill?</i>

254
00:14:28,622 --> 00:14:31,708
<i>Got to travel light.
Can't raise suspicion.</i>

255
00:14:32,501 --> 00:14:34,795
<i>I just need a reliable tool,</i>

256
00:14:34,920 --> 00:14:36,963
<i>something I can count on.</i>

257
00:15:48,952 --> 00:15:50,412
Hey!

258
00:15:50,579 --> 00:15:52,622
Oh, you startled me.

259
00:15:52,789 --> 00:15:54,082
Sorry.

260
00:15:54,207 --> 00:15:56,501
- I was hoping to catch a ride to Tampa.
- Kyle...

261
00:15:56,626 --> 00:15:58,753
I need to get away,
even just for the weekend.

262
00:15:59,880 --> 00:16:00,839
I'm sorry.

263
00:16:00,964 --> 00:16:03,675
There'll be other opportunities,
but not this one.

264
00:16:03,800 --> 00:16:06,136
I can't wait.
Arthur, I need to do this.

265
00:16:07,095 --> 00:16:10,182
Give something back to the world.
Make things right.

266
00:16:12,893 --> 00:16:14,895
I can't do that without your help.

267
00:16:19,441 --> 00:16:22,068
I have to get out of here.

268
00:16:23,278 --> 00:16:25,113
Out of here.

269
00:16:26,865 --> 00:16:29,284
Away from this...

270
00:16:29,409 --> 00:16:30,911
feeling, whatever it is.

271
00:16:31,036 --> 00:16:32,496
And with you, I feel focused,

272
00:16:32,662 --> 00:16:36,583
like I have a sense
of purpose and certainty.

273
00:16:38,126 --> 00:16:39,878
I need you.

274
00:16:40,003 --> 00:16:42,005
I...

275
00:16:43,089 --> 00:16:45,383
I have nothing to give you.

276
00:16:46,676 --> 00:16:49,137
Generosity of spirit, Arthur?

277
00:16:51,097 --> 00:16:54,518
I know those are more than just words
to you. Tell me they're not just...

278
00:16:54,684 --> 00:16:56,269
words.

279
00:17:00,482 --> 00:17:02,400
You need my help?

280
00:17:02,526 --> 00:17:04,444
More than you know.

281
00:17:04,569 --> 00:17:06,530
There's nobody else?

282
00:17:06,696 --> 00:17:09,032
You're the one, Arthur.

283
00:17:10,575 --> 00:17:12,202
The only one.

284
00:17:14,621 --> 00:17:17,332
- Well, come on.
- I knew I could count on you.

285
00:17:30,387 --> 00:17:33,974
According to Dexter's spatter work,
our suspect is at least six feet tall.

286
00:17:34,099 --> 00:17:35,141
Closer to 6'4".

287
00:17:35,267 --> 00:17:36,518
More like 6'4".

288
00:17:36,726 --> 00:17:38,353
The DNA profile
says we're looking

289
00:17:38,478 --> 00:17:40,814
for a Caucasian male
of Northern European descent,

290
00:17:40,939 --> 00:17:42,232
blue eyes...

291
00:17:42,357 --> 00:17:44,359
50 to 70 years old.

292
00:17:44,484 --> 00:17:48,405
So we're looking for
a potentially retired, old, white guy.

293
00:17:48,530 --> 00:17:49,948
In Miami?

294
00:17:50,073 --> 00:17:51,408
Great.

295
00:17:51,533 --> 00:17:53,201
And this is the snowbird season.

296
00:17:53,368 --> 00:17:54,995
Which quadruples
our old-white-guy quotient.

297
00:17:55,120 --> 00:17:58,790
There's got to be something else we can do,
some other angle...

298
00:17:58,957 --> 00:18:00,208
DNA sweep.

299
00:18:00,333 --> 00:18:03,420
We could do
a targeted DNA sweep

300
00:18:03,545 --> 00:18:07,382
of white males, 60-ish,
in the Miami Metro area.

301
00:18:07,507 --> 00:18:09,593
You know how much work that is?

302
00:18:09,718 --> 00:18:11,970
I've got a big weekend planned.
As in twins.

303
00:18:12,178 --> 00:18:14,723
- You got twins lined up?
- Not yet, but that's the plan.

304
00:18:14,889 --> 00:18:18,101
Besides, the ACLU will shut this down
the minute word gets out.

305
00:18:18,226 --> 00:18:19,811
And they always do.

306
00:18:19,936 --> 00:18:21,688
You can't do a roadblock
without drawing some attention.

307
00:18:22,522 --> 00:18:23,815
It's the weekend.

308
00:18:27,360 --> 00:18:29,112
Next week's Thanksgiving,

309
00:18:29,237 --> 00:18:31,740
so the courts will be closed.

310
00:18:33,366 --> 00:18:35,410
Sweeps have worked
in Miami before.

311
00:18:35,535 --> 00:18:37,120
Right, the South Beach rapist,

312
00:18:37,245 --> 00:18:39,998
the robbery-homicide case in '06.

313
00:18:40,123 --> 00:18:42,459
- '07.
- '07.

314
00:18:42,584 --> 00:18:45,128
Wait, wait, who's gonna...
who's gonna pay for all this?

315
00:18:45,253 --> 00:18:48,465
The department's so strapped,
we can't even afford coffee filters.

316
00:18:48,673 --> 00:18:51,760
I used toilet paper to make
the coffee this morning.

317
00:18:52,427 --> 00:18:54,596
If DNA is our only lead,
then DNA is what we'll look for.

318
00:18:54,721 --> 00:18:56,473
Let me worry about the budget.

319
00:18:56,598 --> 00:18:59,601
Masuka, write up a protocol for random
field swabbing that Patrol can follow.

320
00:18:59,726 --> 00:19:01,269
Everything goes through you.

321
00:19:01,394 --> 00:19:03,188
There go my plans.

322
00:19:05,607 --> 00:19:06,983
Happy?

323
00:19:08,652 --> 00:19:10,820
How are we gonna pay for this?

324
00:19:10,945 --> 00:19:13,031
I have no idea.

325
00:19:13,156 --> 00:19:16,451
But I'm about to spend a lot of hours
looking for loose change in the budget.

326
00:19:17,077 --> 00:19:19,120
That's a lot of work.

327
00:19:19,579 --> 00:19:20,789
Want some help?

328
00:19:20,955 --> 00:19:23,625
- Absolutely. Come on in.
- OK.

329
00:19:24,793 --> 00:19:26,503
You know...

330
00:19:26,628 --> 00:19:28,838
the briefing room might be better.

331
00:19:30,340 --> 00:19:31,424
Out in the open?

332
00:19:32,300 --> 00:19:33,677
Yeah?

333
00:19:33,843 --> 00:19:35,220
Better?

334
00:19:46,022 --> 00:19:48,233
<i>I already feel
the cloud of Farrow lifting</i>

335
00:19:48,358 --> 00:19:50,443
<i>in anticipation of tonight.</i>

336
00:19:50,860 --> 00:19:55,699
So what time do we get started
in the morning?

337
00:19:55,824 --> 00:19:57,909
Six o'clock.

338
00:19:59,994 --> 00:20:01,913
It'll be mostly local guys?

339
00:20:02,038 --> 00:20:03,832
Yeah, women too.

340
00:20:03,957 --> 00:20:07,043
<i>The first kill in his cycle
of three is always a woman,</i>

341
00:20:07,210 --> 00:20:08,503
<i>but he won't get the chance.</i>

342
00:20:08,628 --> 00:20:11,256
- Do we all stay at the same hotel?
- I don't know.

343
00:20:11,381 --> 00:20:13,049
Is it close to the build?

344
00:20:15,635 --> 00:20:17,053
It's walking distance.

345
00:20:17,262 --> 00:20:20,181
- Does everybody hang out together or...
- Good Lord, you have a lot of questions.

346
00:20:21,975 --> 00:20:23,518
Sorry.

347
00:20:25,478 --> 00:20:28,231
You told me you were troubled.
About what?

348
00:20:35,697 --> 00:20:38,408
I did something.

349
00:20:39,534 --> 00:20:41,286
Well, let's hear it.

350
00:20:41,453 --> 00:20:42,454
I made a mistake.

351
00:20:42,579 --> 00:20:44,622
- We all make mistakes.
- It was a big one.

352
00:20:44,748 --> 00:20:48,084
You're being purposely vague, Kyle,

353
00:20:48,251 --> 00:20:50,044
like one of my tenth-graders

354
00:20:50,170 --> 00:20:53,798
who's trying to explain
why he didn't do his homework.

355
00:20:53,923 --> 00:20:57,469
<i>I have a feeling I'm gonna
make some tenth-graders very happy.</i>

356
00:20:57,594 --> 00:20:59,053
Pit stop.

357
00:21:19,240 --> 00:21:23,119
- You're a brave man, Kyle.
- How so?

358
00:21:23,244 --> 00:21:25,163
Eating from a vending machine.

359
00:21:25,288 --> 00:21:28,208
Years of training - iron stomach.

360
00:21:29,250 --> 00:21:31,294
Maybe you could show
some of that same bravery

361
00:21:31,461 --> 00:21:33,963
by sharing what's bothering you.

362
00:21:37,258 --> 00:21:40,011
How am I supposed to help you
when I don't know what the problem is?

363
00:21:40,136 --> 00:21:42,096
- It's not that important.
- It's important to me.

364
00:21:42,222 --> 00:21:43,848
Why?

365
00:21:44,015 --> 00:21:47,310
Because helping someone is a good deed,
and God rewards good deeds,

366
00:21:47,435 --> 00:21:50,021
but in order to help, I need to know
the problem. That's how these things work.

367
00:21:50,146 --> 00:21:51,314
I really don't want to talk about it.

368
00:21:51,481 --> 00:21:54,692
You asked me, remember?
That's why I brought you.

369
00:21:54,818 --> 00:21:57,529
- Why don't we just...
- Tell me, Kyle!

370
00:21:59,322 --> 00:22:01,658
I'm gonna get into my van and just
leave you here to fend for yourself.

371
00:22:01,783 --> 00:22:03,827
I killed a man.

372
00:22:14,254 --> 00:22:15,338
You killed someone?

373
00:22:15,505 --> 00:22:18,383
<i>You, of all people, act appalled.</i>

374
00:22:18,508 --> 00:22:21,511
- By mistake.
- How? What happened?

375
00:22:21,636 --> 00:22:24,305
I thought he was the right...

376
00:22:31,104 --> 00:22:33,565
I thought he was an animal.

377
00:22:34,524 --> 00:22:37,068
You... You were hunting?

378
00:22:38,194 --> 00:22:40,697
Yes, it was a hunting accident.

379
00:22:41,781 --> 00:22:44,450
I was so sure.
I'm always so careful.

380
00:22:44,576 --> 00:22:47,245
Then it truly was an accident.

381
00:22:47,370 --> 00:22:49,581
Still, it's left me with this...

382
00:22:51,833 --> 00:22:53,877
feeling.

383
00:22:56,254 --> 00:22:59,299
There are few things
harder to bear than remorse.

384
00:23:00,133 --> 00:23:01,759
Remorse?

385
00:23:01,885 --> 00:23:03,219
Guilt. Remorse.

386
00:23:03,344 --> 00:23:05,513
It's what separates us
from the animals.

387
00:23:08,433 --> 00:23:11,227
Your conscience
is eating away at you.

388
00:23:12,896 --> 00:23:15,648
But you're gonna feel better.

389
00:23:15,773 --> 00:23:17,775
Confession is good for the soul.

390
00:23:17,901 --> 00:23:20,820
<i>All the more proof I have no soul.</i>

391
00:23:21,821 --> 00:23:25,825
<i>Doing good deeds,
scoring points with God.</i>

392
00:23:30,204 --> 00:23:32,874
<i>You and I are way beyond
the point system, Arthur.</i>

393
00:23:33,041 --> 00:23:35,877
<i>The best deed I can do
is rid the world of you.</i>

394
00:23:40,214 --> 00:23:42,091
<i>A fitting kill room.</i>

395
00:23:42,216 --> 00:23:45,136
<i>Small, but I'll be
cutting him down to size.</i>

396
00:23:47,931 --> 00:23:50,808
<i>I just need to pick up a few supplies.</i>

397
00:23:55,229 --> 00:23:58,691
- Hey, Deb.
<i>- How's the weather?</i>

398
00:23:58,816 --> 00:23:59,817
Funny.

399
00:23:59,943 --> 00:24:03,613
You talking climate
with a bunch of dorks and nerds,

400
00:24:03,780 --> 00:24:04,906
you really lead the life.

401
00:24:05,031 --> 00:24:07,909
Is there a reason for this call?
It's getting late.

402
00:24:08,076 --> 00:24:11,496
That jumper out at the warehouse,
you took a bunch of crime-scene photos.

403
00:24:11,663 --> 00:24:13,623
Did you put them all in the file?

404
00:24:15,041 --> 00:24:18,086
I take a lot of photos.
I don't use 'em all.

405
00:24:18,211 --> 00:24:20,421
- But you save them?
- I do.

406
00:24:20,588 --> 00:24:23,174
I want to look through 'em,
see if I can find any ash smudges.

407
00:24:23,299 --> 00:24:25,301
Well, they're all
on the lab computer.

408
00:24:25,426 --> 00:24:27,345
Masuka can access 'em for you.

409
00:24:27,470 --> 00:24:29,847
- I can't ask Masuka.
- Why?

410
00:24:29,973 --> 00:24:31,641
Because I'm not working this case.

411
00:24:32,892 --> 00:24:35,395
- Could've fooled me.
- I know, right?

412
00:24:35,561 --> 00:24:37,271
At least I got Quinn to start
DNA sweeps tomorrow.

413
00:24:37,397 --> 00:24:39,232
<i>That's something anyway, right?</i>

414
00:24:39,357 --> 00:24:41,150
DNA sweeps?

415
00:24:41,275 --> 00:24:43,319
Yeah, we're gonna do
random cheek swabs

416
00:24:43,444 --> 00:24:46,698
on tall white men over 50,
preferably with blue eyes.

417
00:24:46,864 --> 00:24:48,324
Good luck with that.

418
00:24:48,449 --> 00:24:49,701
<i>Thanks.</i>

419
00:24:49,826 --> 00:24:54,038
Hey, you run into
that weather guy, Sonny Skyes,

420
00:24:54,163 --> 00:24:55,832
you tell him he's got a stupid name.

421
00:24:55,957 --> 00:24:57,667
Will do.

422
00:24:57,792 --> 00:24:59,836
<i>But first a little shopping.</i>

423
00:25:06,050 --> 00:25:08,052
Oh.

424
00:25:08,177 --> 00:25:09,387
Are you headed out?

425
00:25:09,512 --> 00:25:11,681
- Yeah, for ice.
- Change of plan for tomorrow.

426
00:25:11,806 --> 00:25:14,684
We're not going to the build.
I got a surprise for you instead.

427
00:25:16,561 --> 00:25:18,187
I don't like surprises.

428
00:25:18,354 --> 00:25:20,982
You'll like this one.
It'll make you feel better.

429
00:25:27,447 --> 00:25:29,073
<i>How will it make me feel better?</i>

430
00:25:29,198 --> 00:25:32,869
<i>Could he have some kind of formula
for remorse or something?</i>

431
00:25:35,079 --> 00:25:37,623
<i>If anyone does, it'd be him.</i>

432
00:25:37,749 --> 00:25:40,668
<i>It's not like I can't kill him tomorrow night.</i>

433
00:25:42,045 --> 00:25:44,797
Good. So far we've saved...

434
00:25:44,922 --> 00:25:46,841
$24,000.

435
00:25:47,967 --> 00:25:50,386
- Not bad.
- It's not enough.

436
00:25:50,511 --> 00:25:53,723
We need at least 12 more.

437
00:25:58,686 --> 00:26:00,354
What?

438
00:26:01,522 --> 00:26:02,857
Your hair.

439
00:26:02,982 --> 00:26:04,901
- My heart skips a beat.
- Stop it.

440
00:26:05,068 --> 00:26:07,028
And thank you.

441
00:26:09,030 --> 00:26:10,615
What time is it? <i>Dios mío.</i>

442
00:26:10,740 --> 00:26:12,700
It's late.

443
00:26:12,867 --> 00:26:14,911
We're the last ones here.

444
00:26:26,839 --> 00:26:28,424
Yo!

445
00:26:29,550 --> 00:26:31,052
You're still here.

446
00:26:31,177 --> 00:26:35,139
Me and a bunch of guys were at the bar.
I came back with some good news.

447
00:26:35,264 --> 00:26:37,767
They want to donate
a vacation day to help pay

448
00:26:37,892 --> 00:26:39,977
for this DNA-sweep thing.

449
00:26:40,103 --> 00:26:41,562
That's amazing, bro.

450
00:26:41,729 --> 00:26:43,898
Fucker shot one of our own.

451
00:26:46,234 --> 00:26:48,486
Look at this. All those days.

452
00:26:48,653 --> 00:26:51,364
It's enough. It fills the gap.

453
00:27:14,095 --> 00:27:15,763
Fuck it.

454
00:27:20,059 --> 00:27:21,978
<i>Papi...</i>

455
00:27:22,103 --> 00:27:23,813
<i>Sí.</i>

456
00:27:29,735 --> 00:27:31,362
Who the fuck is it?

457
00:27:31,487 --> 00:27:33,030
It's me.

458
00:27:33,156 --> 00:27:36,242
I called, but you didn't pick up.

459
00:27:38,161 --> 00:27:41,205
I know it's late,
but I've had the worst day.

460
00:27:41,330 --> 00:27:43,624
I'm sorry, babe, but I...

461
00:27:43,749 --> 00:27:46,169
I could lose my job.

462
00:27:46,335 --> 00:27:48,629
Not like I'm the only one.
Being a journalist these days

463
00:27:48,754 --> 00:27:51,007
is a straight ticket
to the unemployment line.

464
00:27:51,132 --> 00:27:54,260
- You're not gonna lose your job.
- My editor laid it out.

465
00:27:55,094 --> 00:27:57,763
He said either I get
"a lead that bleeds",

466
00:27:57,889 --> 00:28:00,474
or basically I'm done.

467
00:28:01,142 --> 00:28:03,186
So you're here.

468
00:28:06,105 --> 00:28:07,064
What?

469
00:28:07,190 --> 00:28:11,194
Look, Christy, I'm half-asleep
and half in the bag.

470
00:28:11,360 --> 00:28:12,820
I can't give you anything.

471
00:28:14,197 --> 00:28:16,032
How about a little support?

472
00:28:16,157 --> 00:28:18,618
You know, like a hug?

473
00:28:18,743 --> 00:28:20,328
Or an "everything's
gonna be all right"?

474
00:28:20,494 --> 00:28:22,330
Everything's gonna be all right.

475
00:28:23,372 --> 00:28:26,042
- That's bullshit.
- Hey, come here.

476
00:28:28,127 --> 00:28:29,754
It is gonna be all right,

477
00:28:29,879 --> 00:28:31,881
'cause you're a kick-ass reporter,

478
00:28:32,006 --> 00:28:34,091
and I'm gonna help you
dig something up,

479
00:28:34,258 --> 00:28:36,719
just not in Homicide.

480
00:28:41,265 --> 00:28:43,351
Maybe you should stay.

481
00:28:52,735 --> 00:28:55,112
Not if you're on the fence.

482
00:28:55,238 --> 00:28:57,448
I'll see you tomorrow.

483
00:29:04,330 --> 00:29:06,624
<i>Quick cab to
the meteorological conference.</i>

484
00:29:06,749 --> 00:29:08,751
<i>Check in, establish an alibi.</i>

485
00:29:08,876 --> 00:29:10,962
<i>- I'll be back in time to...</i>
- Kyle!

486
00:29:11,087 --> 00:29:12,046
Hey.

487
00:29:12,171 --> 00:29:13,422
You're an early bird too, huh?

488
00:29:13,589 --> 00:29:16,550
Yeah, how else
would I catch the worm?

489
00:29:16,717 --> 00:29:20,721
Yeah, I'm so excited about today's surprise,
I practically sprang out of bed.

490
00:29:21,931 --> 00:29:24,100
- You ready for this?
- So ready.

491
00:29:25,559 --> 00:29:27,687
That's the spirit.

492
00:29:28,229 --> 00:29:29,689
Come on.

493
00:29:30,940 --> 00:29:33,109
<i>Yesterday he's jumping down my throat,</i>

494
00:29:33,234 --> 00:29:35,611
<i>today he's the happy dancing man.</i>

495
00:29:35,778 --> 00:29:37,989
<i>Is that mask of his crumbling?</i>

496
00:29:58,050 --> 00:29:59,552
Oh, Frank.

497
00:30:05,141 --> 00:30:08,436
So I was thinking, it might not be
a bad idea to ask Masuka...

498
00:30:08,561 --> 00:30:11,981
Oh, fuck me. Don't you have other cases
you should be working on?

499
00:30:12,106 --> 00:30:13,899
I'm trying to help you.

500
00:30:14,066 --> 00:30:16,736
Maybe you should ask Masuka
if you could get Dexter's old discard photos

501
00:30:16,861 --> 00:30:19,530
from the Tarla Grant crime scene.

502
